Dataframe Transformations

Change Rater 11 to an integer. Structure exploration showed it imported as a factor.

Chimps$Rater11 <- as.integer(Chimps$Rater11)

Create functions and add columns

Create a function to produce row medians. The arguements to the function call x and na.rm = FALSE to indicate to calculate function regardless of any NA values in the row. The function calls says to apply x over rows, and to produce a median, and na.rm is set to equal itself.

rowMedian <- function(x, na.rm = FALSE)
    apply(x, 1, median, na.rm = na.rm)

Create a function to produce row standard deviations, in a similar fashion as above, except apply goes over rows using sd to produce a standard deviation.

rowSD <- function(x, na.rm = FALSE)
  apply(x, 1, sd, na.rm = na.rm)

I add columns to the dataframe using the functions above + an already built in function for rowMeans. Here RaterMean = Average value of greying in each Chimpanzee photo. Accordingly, each new column is produced by calling the function and applying it to columns 7:14.

Chimps$RaterMean <- rowMeans(Chimps[,7:14])
Chimps$RaterMedian <- rowMedian(Chimps[,7:14])
Chimps$RaterSD <- rowSD(Chimps[,7:14])

Analyze the data + cooresponding visuals

Does age coorelate with greying (main objective)?

I.e. Is hair greying in Pan troglodytes a proper indicator of aging?

ChimpMod1 <- lm(RaterMean~Age, data = Chimps)

Test: I run a linear model to look at relationship between greying (ratermean) and age. Then, I show the anova table for the two way anova.

Result: I reject the null hypothesis that there is no relationship between greying and age.

Visual:

Mod1Plot <- ggplot(Chimps, aes(RaterMean, Age, color= Age)) + geom_point(col = "cadetblue4") + theme_bw(12) + stat_smooth(method = 'lm') + labs(x= "Amount of Greying") + annotate("text", x=1.5, y=49, label=paste("p = < 2.2e-16"))

Test: One-way ANOVA

Note: Transform face_coloration from continuous to factoral data.

Result: Reject the null hypothesis that darker face coloration does not coorelate with the presence of grey hairs. The probability of observed values (p-value) is extreme: 3.667e-15.

Visual:

Mod2Plot <- qplot(x= Face_Coloration_LizT, y= RaterMean, data=Chimps, geom="boxplot", fill=Face_Coloration_LizT) + theme_bw(12) + labs(y = "Amount Hair Greying", x = "Amount of facial pigmentation") + scale_fill_manual(values = c("beige", "cadetblue4", "azure4", "black"))  + guides(fill=guide_legend(title="Facial Pigmentation Score")) + theme(legend.position = "bottom") + annotate("text", x=1.4, y=4.2, label=paste("p = 3.667e-15"))

Facial Pigmentation and Hair Greying in Pan troglodytes

Do males and females differ in the degree of hair greying exhibited (sub-objective #2)?

t.test(RaterMean~Sex, data=subset(Chimps, Sex %in% c("F", "M")))
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  RaterMean by Sex
## t = 0.37389, df = 109.44, p-value = 0.7092
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.2976822  0.4361172
## sample estimates:
## mean in group F mean in group M 
##        2.396226        2.327009

Test: Unpaired T-test.

Result: Accept the Null hypothesis that males and females do not differ in degree of hair greying exhibited, probability of observed data (p-value) is 0.7092.

Visual:

AgePlot <- qplot(x= Sex, y= RaterMean, data=Chimps, geom="boxplot", fill=Sex) + theme_bw(12) + annotate("text", x=1.4, y=3.6, label=paste("p = 0.7092")) + labs(y = "Amount of Greying") + scale_fill_manual(values = c("beige", "cadetblue4"))
AgePlot

Greying variation in Male and Female Pan troglodytes

AgePopPlot <- ggplot(Chimps, aes(x= Population, y= Age)) + geom_bar(position = "dodge", width = 0.75, stat = "identity", aes(fill= Sex)) + scale_fill_manual(values = c("beige", "cadetblue4")) + theme_bw(12)

Test: Two-way Anova

Result: Reject the null hypothesis. There is a difference in hair greying, based on interactions between population and age. Probability of observed data, given the null hypothesis, is <2e-16.

Conclusion

Hair greying and age show a positive coorelation such that the p-value indicates the probability you observe the given data, given the null hypothesis, is very low.

Also: 1) Darker facial coloration does correlate with the presence of grey hairs; 2) male and female chimps do not differ in the amount of grey hairs exhibited; 3) greying differs significantly between populations, & 4) greying varies according to population type (captive vs.wild).
